03964nam a22006615i 9780813544960DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20082008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135449607 a10.36019/97808135449602doi  a(DE-B1597)529533  a(OCoLC)1096456027  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN1994b.P6535 2008 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.432221 aPomerance, Murray, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Horse Who Drank the Sky :bFilm Experience Beyond Narrative and Theory /cMurray Pomerance. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (278 p.) :b4  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tOverture -- t1. A Voluptuous Gaze -- t2. The Hero in the China Sea -- t3. A Great Face -- t4. The Smoke and the Knife -- t5. A Call from Everywhere -- t6. As Time Goes By -- t7. The Speaking Eye -- t8. Not an Unusual Story -- t9. The Horse Who Drank the Sky -- tWorks Cited and Consulted -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is most important about cinema is that we are alive with it. For all its dramatic, literary, political, sociological, and philosophical weight, film is ultimately an art that provokes, touches, and riddles the viewer through an image that transcends narrative and theory. In The Horse Who Drank the Sky, Murray Pomerance brings attention to the visceral dimension of movies and presents a new and unanticipated way of thinking about what happens when we watch them. By looking at point of view, the gaze, the voice from nowhere, diegesis and its discontents, ideology, the system of the apparatus, invisible editing, and the technique of overlapping sound, he argues that it is often the minuscule or transitional moments in motion pictures that penetrate most deeply into viewers' experiences. In films that include Rebel Without a Cause, Dead Man, Chinatown, The Graduate, North by Northwest, Dinner at Eight, Jaws, M, Stage Fright, Saturday Night Fever, The Band Wagon, The Bourne Identity, and dozens more, Pomerance invokes complexities that many of the best of critics have rarely tackled and opens a revealing view of some of the most astonishing moments in cinema.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aMotion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813544960423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813544960.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK